# .gitkeep placeholder for the "vscode" GNU Stow package
#
# Purpose:
# - Keep the directory in git so this folder can act as a Stow package for VS Code user settings.
# - Place VS Code user files here so Stow can create symlinks into:
#     ~/Library/Application Support/Code/User/
#
# Typical files to add in this directory:
# - settings.json
# - keybindings.json
# - snippets/ (folder with snippet files)
# - globalStorage/ (if you track extensions/settings that write there)
#
# Example layout inside the repo (this package):
# dotfiles/
# └── vscode/
#     └── Library/
#         └── Application Support/
#             └── Code/
#                 └── User/
#                     ├── settings.json
#                     └── keybindings.json
#
# How to stow (from the repo root):
# - Default (when running from repo root and you want to target $HOME):
#     stow -v --target="$HOME" vscode
#
# - Or explicitly specify the package directory (-d) and target (-t):
#     stow -v -d /path/to/repo -t "$HOME" vscode
#
# Use `stow -n` for a dry run to preview changes:
#     stow -n -v -t "$HOME" vscode
#
# Notes:
# - If files already exist at the target, back them up before stowing or use the bootstrap script that handles backups.
# - Keep this placeholder to ensure the package directory structure is present in the repo.
